tributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aStereotypes and cultural imperialism often provide a framework of fixed characteristics for postmodern life, yet fail to address the implications of questions such as, "Where are you from?" Growing Up Transnational challenges the assumptions behind this fixed framework to look at the interconnectivity, conflict, and contradictions within current discussions of identity and kinship.This collection offers a fresh, feminist perspective on family relations, identity politics, and cultural locations in a global era. Using an interdisciplinary approach from fields including gender studies, postcolonial theory, and literary theory, this volume questions the concept of hybridity and the tangible implications of assumed identities. The rich personal narratives of the authors explore hyphenated identities, hybridized families, and the challenges and rewards of lives on and beyond borders. The result is a new transnational sensibility that explores the redefinition of the self, the family, and the nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aDevasahayam, Theresa W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDong, Lan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, May, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKenny, Erin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKriž, Katrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManandhar, Uday, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarcus, Alan P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPapayiannis, Noula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.